snippet.textDisplay:
165 is the correct choice for a new division. Heavyweight to Light Heavyweight is a bigger gap in terms of actual weight, but the reality is there are far less top athletic men at that weight in the world, and even less of those larger men who choose MMA over other sports. The competition is just not there. 
The average male weight in the US is 195 (ranging high due to obesity), but that is NOT a fighting weight: fighters cut on average 10-20 pounds, usually towards the higher end of that range...so, the average fighting weight for a normal American man would be a 175 pound division roughly. The average male adult weight in other countries is much smaller than the US; for example, in Brazil it is only 160.3, in Germany 181.7, and South Korea it is 151.2. So, across the world the average male's fighting weight would be in the Featherweight (145) to WW (170) range, and that is clearly reflected if you look at the number of fighters per division in the UFC and the talent depth of each division.
The UFC should absolutely add a 165 lb division, bump 170 to 175, and probably add a 195 lb division...225 maybe.
